        <a href="index.html">← Back to Class2Career</a>
    </nav>

    <div class="container">
        <h1>I Dug Ditches in College. Then I Earned Two PhDs. Here's What I Learned About Business.</h1>
        
        <p class="subtitle">A message from Ignis Spindler, PhD</p>

        <p>Let me tell you something nobody told me.</p>

        <p>I dug ditches to pay for college. I taught public school. I've worked in scientific consulting, risk management, financial analytics, and bioinformatics. Somewhere along the way, I picked up more than 250 graduate credits in physics and statistics — and earned two PhDs.</p>

        <p>And here's the thing: <strong>none of those achievements required the PhD.</strong></p>

        <div class="stats">
            <div class="stat">
                <div class="number">$40K</div>
                <div class="label">Starting salary (teaching)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
                <div class="number">$200K+</div>
                <div class="label">Current management position</div>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
                <div class="number">2 PhDs</div>
                <div class="label">250+ graduate credits</div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <blockquote>
            "Most of my bosses have been paid more, they knew less, and they weren't exceptional. They just knew how to talk about business in the language of their executives."
        </blockquote>

        <h2>Here's What Business School Doesn't Teach You</h2>

        <div class="story-box">
            <p>I got my first managerial role with two PhDs and <em>no idea</em> how business actually worked.</p>

            <p>Not because I lacked intelligence. Not because I lacked work ethic. But because nobody had ever taught me the language of business.</p>

            <p>I didn't know what a P&L was. I couldn't explain my technical skills in terms that mattered to executives. I spent my first year fumbling through meetings while people with less expertise got promoted over me — not because they were smarter, but because they knew how to talk the talk.</p>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Traditional business education gets it wrong:</strong></p>

        <ul>
            <li><strong>It charges $200,000 for common sense.</strong> The principles in these workbooks can be explained in an afternoon.</li>
            <li><strong>It trains people for jobs that are disappearing.</strong> Middle management is shrinking. You need to be a change maker, not a manager.</li>
            <li><strong>It skips the practical stuff.</strong> Nobody teaches you how to talk about value. How to prove your worth. How to actually get things done.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What You Get</h2>

        <ul class="workbook-list">
            <li>
                <strong>Workbook 1: Business Foundation</strong>
                Understand how businesses actually work — not the textbook version, but the reality.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Workbook 2: Sales Dimension</strong>
                Learn the metrics that matter and how to prove your value in dollars.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Workbook 3: Value Dimension</strong>
                Create impact, not just activity. Learn to measure what matters.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Workbook 4: Product Dimension</strong>
                The missing piece in every business education. How products are built and scaled.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Workbook 5: Personal Growth</strong>
                Define your vision, understand your tolerances, and build the career you want.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <p>Plus: The <strong>Reflection Journal</strong> — hands-on exercises for every concept, turning knowledge into action.</p>

        <h2>Who This Is For</h2>

        <ul>
            <li><strong>PhDs transitioning to industry</strong> — Learn to speak the language without losing your expertise.</li>
            <li><strong>Scientists and researchers</strong> — Your skills are valuable. Learn to communicate them.</li>
            <li><strong>Career changers from academia or public sector</strong> — Get the business foundation you need.</li>
            <li><strong>First-generation professionals</strong> — Navigate corporate culture without a family playbook.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The Price of Staying Silent</h2>

        <p>You can keep fumbling through business meetings, wondering why nobody understands your value.</p>

        <p>You can spend years learning things the hard way — like I did.</p>

        <p>Or you can spend <strong>$27</strong> and get the crash course I wish I'd had.</p>

        <div class="cta-box">
            <div class="price">$27</div>
            <p>One-time payment. Lifetime access.</p>
            <a href="#" class="btn">Get the Complete Toolkit</a>
            <p style="margin-top: 1rem; font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--soft-gold);">All 5 workbooks + Reflection Journal + Book recommendations</p>
        </div>

        <p class="signature">
            <strong>Ignis Spindler, PhD</strong>
            Two PhDs. First-generation college grad. Blue collar roots. Real results.
        </p>
    </div>

